observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Direct the HRMO to submit each year to the Municipal Accountant a certified computation of the yearend balance of leave credits of officials and employees;
Accrue each year the money value of accumulated leave credits of pursuant to IPSAS 39;
Prepare adjusting entries to accrue the money value of accumulated leave credits as of yearend and correct entries previously made and furnish COA with the JEV;
Ensure that monetization of leave credits is properly supported with valid documents in compliance to Omnibus Rules on Leave and COA Circular No. 2012-001 before processing the payment; and
VL credits should be exhausted first before SL credits are used in accordance with CSC Resolution No. 00-0034 dated January 5, 2000 and that monetization of leave credits shall be availed of only once a year pursuant to CSC and DBM Joint Circular No. 2-97 dated June 25, 1997.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the required adjusting entries to reclassify tangible items, with costs below the capitalization threshold and already issued to end-users, in accordance with the illustrative entries outlined in Annex C of COA Circular No. 2024-06 dated March 14, 2024;
Require the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the inaccurate JEV previously recorded for the reclassification of expendable properties;
Direct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a revised RPCPPE including the IIRUP, following the prescribed format;
Require the General Service Officer to prepare and maintain Property Cards per asset classification using the prescribed format; and
Enhance internal controls over the recording and reporting of semi-expendable items to prevent recurrence of similar issues.

Recommendations:
We recommended and it was agreed that Management:
Address all issues which caused the delay in the completion of these projects and institute measures promptly to curtail the days of delay;
Fully implement all on-going projects for CY 2024 and 2023 under 20% Development Fund and submit pictures after completion;
Instruct the MEO to implement a close monitoring of projects, furnish the Office of the Auditor copies of approved suspension orders and/or time extension and impose liquidated damages if the project is completed beyond target date, if any; and
Ensure the accuracy and consistency of the reports through thorough review, reconciliation and timely coordination of responsible personnel.

Recommendations:
We recommended and it was agreed that Management undertake the following, to wit:
Require the Municipal Accountant to transfer all unexpended balances of the current year's QRF and DRRMF - MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability - DRRM” at the end of each year, while ensuring sufficient cash backing for the transfer to maintain fund integrity and availability for future DRRM initiatives;
Cease using the LDRRMF for expenditures that do not fall under the eligible projects and activities outlined in the JMC;
Institute stronger financial and internal controls to prevent future misallocation of the LDRRMF;
Establish a systematic monitoring mechanism for LDRRMF charges to ensure accurate tracking and accountability;
Direct the LDRRMO to promptly submit the Monthly Report of Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF, duly certified correct by the Municipal Accountant, on or before the 15th day following the end of each month; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the detailed balances of the LDRRMF, following Annex D of COA Circular No. 2012-002, to ensure fair presentation and enhance the Financial Statements’ clarity for users.

Recommendations:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to the following:
Direct the members of the GAD Focal Point Person and the members of the GFPS to avail of trainings, seminars and other capacity-building activities on GAD yearly and include such in the organization-focused PPAs to be incorporated in the GPB for 2026;
Direct the GFPS to conduct annual gender audits prior and after the crafting of the GPB and GAR to assess the effectiveness of GAD programs and fund utilization;
Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to spearhead the setting-up and maintenance of the LGU’s GAD database, maximizing all available resources to collect sex-disaggregated data and GAD related information and incorporate these activities in the GPB for 2026;
Assign a dedicated unit or personnel/s within the Gender and Development Focal Point System (GFPS) to oversee data gathering, validation, and analysis;
Use the HGDG tool to assess and validate the gender responsiveness of LGU projects before attribution and for attribution;
Impose and monitor the conduct regular meetings with minutes of the meetings of the members of the GFPS for the purpose of regular internal reviews that will ensure that at least 5% of the total LGU budget appropriations are correctly allocated to GAD PPAs in accordance with the guidelines;
Completely fill-up and submit on time complete attachments of the revised GPB and GAR templates following the guidelines prescribed in JMC 2016-01; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain records/ schedule as to the breakdown of the PPAs attributed to GAD and readily make it available for the audit team’s review.

We recommended that the Management: 

Strictly comply with the documentary requirements for the cash advance, replenishment and liquidation of the PCF; 
Strictly adhere to the provisions for PCF of COA Circular No. 2002-003 and NGAS for LGUs;
Liquidate the PCF at year-end incompliance with the fair presentation of the financial statements in IPSAS 1; and 
Take into consideration the decrease of the PCF’s size/ amount to cater only a reasonable amount of expenses monthly.

We recommended that the Management: 

Strictly comply with the documentary requirements for the cash advance of confidential expenses and submit the same to the audit team within the period prescribed in COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01;
Strictly adhere the provisions of fair presentation of the financial statements in IPSAS 1 and recognize the un-liquidated 4th quarter cash advance for confidential funds in the 2023 financial statements; 
The Municipal Accountant furnish the audit team with the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) upon recording of the liquidation of the CA for CF in the books of the Municipality; and
Take into consideration the possible increase in the SDO’s amount of bond to increase her maximum cash accountability.

We recommended that Management should: 

Direct the Accounting Section to compute the liquidated damages and collect from the concerned suppliers the amount due them and strictly impose liquidated damages for late deliveries; 
Ensure that the terms and conditions indicated in the purchase orders and contracts are strictly complies with; 
Require the suppliers to post a warranty security as well as submission of letter of extension in case suppliers cannot meet the required delivery term to avoid penalty; and 
Instruct the Supply Officer to strictly monitor the deliveries of purchased goods to avoid delays.

We recommended that Management: 

Strictly adhere to the provisions of IPSAS 1; 
Prepare demand letters for the liquidation of the Cash Advances accounts except those for Confidential funds and furnish the audit team with such; 
Exhaust all possible remedies to collect receivables, if not recognize impairment for the Other Receivables account; 
Secure the approval of COA to write-off/derecognize from the books the dormant accounts pursuant COA Circular 2023-008; 
Ensure that current transactions and those below ten years are properly documented and appropriately acted upon immediately to avoid being dormant; and 
Furnish the audit team with the updated monitoring, schedules, supporting documents, and aging of such receivable accounts on a timely basis.

We recommended that the Management shall:

Periodically review performance targets and initiate mitigating measures to avoid deficiency of cash; 
Closely coordinate with the Local Finance Committee and Municipal Accountant thru regular meetings, consultations or dialogue; 
Regularly monitor cash in bank balances to ensure that there is sufficient cash to cover all trust liabilities before any disbursement could be made; and 
Ensure that subsequent enactment of any Supplemental Budgets on the account of unexpended balance or savings, should be supported with adequate cash backing, otherwise, this Office will be compelled to enforce appropriate audit actions that may be applied thereto.

We recommended that Management: 

Instruct the concerned officials and employees to refund the excess amount of Per Diems claimed for their respective travels; 
Strictly avoid granting travelling allowances more than what is allowed; 
Submit to COA the lacking documents to support the Liquidation Reports; 
Observe the complete documentary requirements in granting and liquidating cash advances, specifically for travel; and 
Direct the accounting office to adhere strictly in recording expenses using the prescribed account codes and titles and adjust the correct balance of the expense accounts affected.

We recommended that Management:
(a) Strictly adhere to the provisions on the grant and liquidation of cash advances as prescribed by Section 89 of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
(b) Compel the officers and employees concerned for the immediate liquidation and settlement of their outstanding cash advances;
(c) Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the granting and liquidation of cash advances to avoid granting additional cash advances to officers and employees with prior unliquidated cash advances; and (d) Enforce deduction from the salary of employees in cases of failure to liquidate within the prescribed period.

We recommended that Management: 
(1) Direct the HRMO to submit each year to the Municipal Accountant a certified computation of the yearend balance of leave credits of officials and employees;
(2) Accrue each year the money value of accumulated leave credits of pursuant to IPSAS 39;
(3) Prepare adjusting entries to accrue the money value of accumulated leave credits as of yearend and correct entries previously made and furnish COA with the JEV;
(4) Ensure that monetization of leave credits are properly supported with valid documents in compliance to Omnibus Rules on Leave and COA Circular No. 2012-001 before processing the payment; and 
(5) VL credits should be exhausted first before SL credits are used in accordance with CSC Resolution No. 00-0034 dated January 5, 2000 and that monetization of leave credits shall be availed of only once a year pursuant to CSC and DBM Joint Circular No. 2-97 dated June 25, 1997.

We recommended that Management:
(a) Strictly adhere to the provisions of fair presentation of the financial statements in IPSAS 1 and the periodic monitoring, reconciliation, adjustment, and aging of receivables as stated in COA Circular 2016-005;
(b) Exhaust all possible remedies to collect receivables and demand liquidation of such accounts;
(c) For receivables determined to be beyond recovery per COA Circular 2016-005, recognize impairment and facilitate the filing of request for authority to write-off following the guidelines and procedures set forth in the said Circular; and
(d) Furnish the audit team with the updated monitoring, schedules, supporting documents, and aging of such receivable accounts.

Therefore, we recommended to the Management that:

a.	Physical count of inventory, property, plant and equipment be conducted immediately and the required reports be completed, reconciled and submitted to COA for our validation;

b.	The Accounting and General Services Offices adopt systems and procedures as required in NGAS Manual for the proper accounting and recording of Inventories and PPEs, maintaining the necessary ledger cards and schedules for substantiation;
